## Codra Language Charter

**Purpose:** establish trust, precision, and professional credibility while preserving Codra’s underlying design soul through restraint and clarity.

Codra speaks like a **serious systems tool built by people who understand infrastructure**, not like a metaphor engine, onboarding coach, or lifestyle app.

### Core Principle

Codra uses **industry-standard language exclusively**.
Any emotional tone emerges from *clarity, consistency, and cause-effect visibility*, not wording.

If a term would appear in:
• engineering documentation
• API references
• DevOps tooling
• workflow orchestration platforms

…it is eligible.

If it would not, it is banned.

---

## Voice and Tone Rules

Codra is **calm, precise, and untheatrical**.

No hype.
No anthropomorphism.
No motivational language.
No “friendly helper” voice.

Codra does not congratulate.
Codra does not encourage.
Codra reports reality.

Correct tone examples:
• “Execution completed”
• “3 nodes failed”
• “Dependency unresolved”
• “Trigger activated”
• “Pipeline paused”

Incorrect tone examples:
• “Nice work!”
• “You’re all set”
• “Oops, something went wrong”
• “Let’s try again”
• “Magic happens here”

If it sounds like onboarding copy, it does not belong in Codra.

---

## Approved Verb Set (Action Language)

Codra actions describe **what actually happens** in a system.

Preferred verbs include:
run
execute
trigger
connect
configure
define
validate
deploy
retry
pause
resume
resolve
fail
log

Avoid soft verbs that imply guidance or emotion.

Disallowed verbs include:
start (use *run* or *execute*)
build (unless literal build artifacts)
help
guide
explore
discover
create magic
automate for you

Codra never claims agency on the user’s behalf.

---

## Approved Noun Set (Object Language)

Codra names things as **technical objects**, not experiences.

Preferred nouns include:
pipeline
workflow
node
step
input
output
dependency
state
execution
trigger
event
log
error
configuration
variable

Disallowed nouns include:
spell
ritual
flow state
magic
assistant
wizard
journey
canvas (borderline, avoid if possible)

If a noun sounds like it belongs in a productivity blog, it is suspect.

---

## Error and Failure Language

Failure is normal. Codra treats it as data.

Errors are:
• direct
• specific
• non-apologetic

Correct:
“Execution failed at node 4: missing API key”
“Dependency cycle detected”
“Trigger condition not met”

Incorrect:
“Something went wrong”
“Oops”
“Don’t worry, we’ll fix this”

Codra does not soothe. Codra informs.

---

## UI Microcopy Rules

Buttons are verbs.
Labels are nouns.
Statuses are states.

Good:
Run pipeline
Pause execution
Retry failed node

Bad:
Go
Try again
Fix it
Make it work

Empty states should be **descriptive, not instructive**.

Correct:
“No pipelines defined”

Incorrect:
“Let’s build your first pipeline!”

---

## Metaphor Containment Rule (Critical)

Metaphor is **never allowed in user-facing language**.

Metaphor is permitted only in:
• internal design rationale
• visual composition
• interaction pacing
• spatial layout

The *structure* may feel like a notebook or synth.
The *words* must read like documentation.

This is non-negotiable.

---

## Accent Color Semantics (Language Adjacent)

Coral is treated as **a semantic signal**, not branding.

Coral may only appear where language indicates:
• execution
• activation
• failure requiring action
• selected operational focus

Coral must never appear near:
• descriptive text
• labels
• passive UI chrome

If coral appears without a verb nearby, it is wrong.

---

## Final Test (Ship Gate)

Before shipping any UI text, ask:

“Would a senior engineer roll their eyes at this?”

If yes, rewrite.

“Could this text appear in a log file or API doc?”

If no, delete or rephrase.
